INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e428746b-61f1-40f0-8d08-cc1e15b3f009',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jenkins Matrix Builds — Parallel Jobs and Test Sharding at Scale$escape$,
  $escape$Jenkins' `matrix` directive (Pipeline 2.12+) lets you define a cross-product of axes, spawning isolated agents per combination — no scripted loops required. Define axes for OS, JDK version, or test suite partition, and Jenkins schedules each cell concurrently across available executors.

For test sharding, pair matrix with `excludes` to drop redundant combinations, then pass the `SHARD_INDEX` and `SHARD_TOTAL` environment variables into your test runner (e.g., pytest-split, Jest --shard). Each cell runs only its slice, then `junit` merges reports post-build.

Use `parallel` blocks inside a stage for ad-hoc fan-out without the combinatorial overhead — ideal when you need three fixed test buckets, not a full matrix. Cap concurrency with `options { throttleJobProperty(...) }` via the Throttle Concurrent Builds plugin to avoid starving other pipelines on shared agents.

Critical: set `failFast true` inside `matrix` so a failing cell kills siblings immediately, preventing wasted executor time on a build you'll re-run anyway.$escape$,
  $escape$pipeline {
  agent none
  stages {
    stage('Matrix Test') {
      matrix {
        axes {
          axis { name 'SHARD_INDEX'; values '1','2','3' }
          axis { name 'JDK'; values '17','21' }
        }
        agent { label "jdk-${JDK}" }
        options { timeout(time: 20, unit: 'MINUTES') }
        failFast true
        stages {
          stage('Test') {
            steps {
              sh "./gradlew test -Pshard=${SHARD_INDEX} -PshardTotal=3"
            }
            post { always { junit 'build/test-results/**/*.xml' } }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
