INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '880fe40f-722d-4869-98cc-f1c12420ef62',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jenkins Self-Hosted Agents — When to Use Them and What They Cost You$escape$,
  $escape$Jenkins' built-in controller can run builds directly, but `agent { label 'linux' }` points to a dedicated node registered via JNLP or SSH. Self-hosted agents make sense when builds need specific hardware (GPU, ARM), proprietary tools, or access to air-gapped internal services that Jenkins SaaS agents can't reach.

The hidden cost is maintenance: every agent node requires OS patching, JDK version alignment with the controller, and plugin-compatible remoting JARs. Drift between nodes causes `NoSuchMethodError` at runtime — pin `remoting.jar` versions via the `jenkins.remoting.version` system property and lock JDK versions with a shared Ansible role or Docker image.

For security, agents run as a dedicated `jenkins` OS user with no sudo. Enable `Agent → Controller Security` in `Manage Jenkins › Security` to prevent agent code from reading controller secrets. Use credential binding via the `withCredentials` step rather than environment variables in `Jenkinsfile`, so secrets never appear in `env` dumps. Isolate untrusted PR builds to ephemeral Docker agents (`docker.image('node:22').inside`) to prevent workspace poisoning across jobs.$escape$,
  $escape$pipeline {
  agent { label 'linux-docker' }
  stages {
    stage('Build') {
      steps {
        withCredentials([string(credentialsId: 'NPM_TOKEN', variable: 'NPM_TOKEN')]) {
          sh 'npm ci'
        }
      }
    }
    stage('Untrusted PR') {
      when { changeRequest() }
      agent { docker { image 'node:22-alpine'; reuseNode false } }
      steps {
        sh 'npm test'
      }
    }
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
