INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f337fe12-5466-477d-aa89-37df5079337d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jenkins Monorepo CI — Affected Detection with Turborepo and Selective Stage Runs$escape$,
  $escape$Running your full Jenkins pipeline on every commit in a monorepo burns agent minutes and developer patience. The fix: compute the affected package set first, then conditionally execute downstream stages.

In a `Jenkinsfile`, use `sh 'npx turbo run build --filter=...[HEAD^1]'` to let Turborepo's affected graph determine what changed since the previous commit. For Nx, swap in `npx nx affected --target=build --base=HEAD~1`. Capture the output, parse it, and set pipeline-level environment variables to gate stages.

Pair this with Jenkins' `when { expression }` directive on each stage. A `lint` stage only runs if `env.AFFECTED_LINT == 'true'`, a `deploy` stage only fires if the `api` package is in the affected set. No custom shell scripts sprawling across the repo — the logic lives in the `Jenkinsfile` and is auditable.

For caching, mount a persistent Jenkins agent workspace volume and set `TURBO_CACHE_DIR` or `NX_CACHE_DIRECTORY` to a path that survives between builds. This gives you local task-level caching without a remote cache server.$escape$,
  $escape$pipeline {
  agent any
  environment {
    AFFECTED = sh(script: 'npx turbo run build --dry=json --filter=...[HEAD^1] | jq -r ".packages[]"', returnStdout: true).trim()
  }
  stages {
    stage('Test') {
      when { expression { env.AFFECTED.contains('packages/api') } }
      steps { sh 'npx turbo run test --filter=api' }
    }
    stage('Deploy') {
      when { expression { env.AFFECTED.contains('packages/api') } }
      steps { sh './scripts/deploy.sh api' }
    }
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
